In .NET 10, `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` is deprecated (Android itself deprecated it in API 30+). The recommended approach is now:

**1. Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (built-in since .NET 8)**

MAUI automatically scrolls content to keep the focused input visible. Make sure you haven't disabled it:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs – this is ON by default, just don't turn it off
builder.UseMauiApp<App>();
```

If you previously disabled it, re-enable per-page:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:android="clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.AndroidSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls"
             android:Application.WindowSoftInputModeAdjust="Resize">
```

**2. Preferred fix for chat UIs — wrap in a `Grid` with proper layout:**

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
    <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..." />
</Grid>
```

**3. If auto-scroll still isn't enough, handle insets explicitly (Android):**

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, imeInsets.Bottom);
        return insets;
    }
}
```

**TL;DR:** Don't use `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize`. Rely on MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`, and if your chat layout still gets obscured, handle IME insets via `ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` in your Android `MainActivity`.
